# Experimental Platform Support 

This folder contains extended platform support that goes beyond the
hardware-confirmed fixes in the main `me_cleaner.py`. The changes here
are based on community reverse engineering and consensus — not direct
hardware flashing by this repo's maintainer.

**Use at your own risk. Always make a full backup of your firmware before
flashing. An incorrect HAP patch that silently writes to the wrong location
will appear to succeed but ME will not be disabled.**

---

## me_cleaner_experimental.py

A drop-in replacement for `me_cleaner.py` that adds support for newer
Intel platforms on top of the stable hardware-confirmed fork.

### What's in the stable fork (unchanged here)

| ME Version | Platform | HAP Location | Status |
|-----------|----------|-------------|--------|
| ME 12 LP | Cannon Lake / Whiskey Lake (8th/9th gen) | `fpsba+0x70` PCHSTRP28 bit 16 | ✅ Hardware confirmed |
| ME 12 H | Cannon Lake H / Z390 desktop | `fpsba+0x80` PCHSTRP32 bit 16 | ✅ Hardware confirmed |
| ME 13 | Ice Lake (10th gen LP) | `fpsba+0x70` PCHSTRP28 bit 16 | ✅ Community confirmed |
| ME 14 | Comet Lake LP (10th gen) | `fpsba+0x70` PCHSTRP28 bit 16 | ✅ Hardware confirmed |

### What's new and experimental

| ME Version | Platform | HAP Location | Status |
|-----------|----------|-------------|--------|
| ME 15 | Tiger Lake (11th gen) | `fpsba+0x7C` PCHSTRP31 bit 16 | ⚠️ Community confirmed, not hw tested here |
| ME 16 | Alder Lake (12th gen) | Flash Descriptor offset `0x017E` byte `0x01` | ⚠️ Community confirmed, not hw tested here |
| ME 16.1 | Raptor Lake (13th gen) | Flash Descriptor offset `0x017E` byte `0x01` | ⚠️ Community confirmed, not hw tested here |
| ME 18 | Meteor Lake (Core Ultra) | Flash Descriptor offset `0x017E` byte `0x01` | ⚠️ Community confirmed, not hw tested here |

### Key change for ADL/RPL/MTL (ME 16+)

On Alder Lake and newer, Intel moved the HAP bit **out of PCHSTRP
entirely**. It is no longer a strap bit — it is a byte in the Flash
Descriptor itself at offset `0x017E`. Setting this byte to `0x01` enables
HAP and disables ME.

Previous community guesses (including `fpsba+0xDC` from XutaxKamay's
PR #384) were incorrect. The descriptor-based location has since been
confirmed by multiple community members independently.

---

## Usage

Identical to the original me_cleaner — it is a single Python file with no
extra dependencies:

```bash
# Set HAP only (recommended for IFWI firmware — newer platforms)
python3 me_cleaner_experimental.py -s firmware.bin -O firmware_hap.bin

# Set HAP and strip modules (older platforms only — not for IFWI)
python3 me_cleaner_experimental.py -S firmware.bin -O firmware_hap.bin

# Check status only — does not modify anything
python3 me_cleaner_experimental.py --check firmware.bin
```

> **Note:** On gen 4+ (ME 12 and newer) the tool automatically detects
> IFWI firmware format and skips module stripping with a warning, only
> setting the HAP bit. This is the correct and safe behaviour for modern
> ThinkPads and other IFWI-based platforms.

---

## How to verify it worked (without flashing)

After running the tool, check with MEAnalyzer before you flash anything:

```
MEAnalyzer.py firmware_hap.bin
```

Look for:

```
HAP/AltMeDisable: Yes
```

If it says `No` — the patch did not apply correctly. Do not flash.

---

## After flashing — how to confirm ME is disabled

```bash
# Should return nothing on a fully disabled machine
lspci | grep -i mei

# Will report "ME not present" or exit immediately if MEI is gone
sudo ./intelmetool -m
```

On 8th gen+ ThinkPads with HAP correctly set:
- `lspci` returns nothing for MEI
- BIOS ME version field is blank
- intelmetool cannot find a device to talk to

This is the expected and correct result. See
[ME_Disable_Comparison.md](../ME_Disable_Comparison.md) for a detailed
explanation of why newer platforms show a more complete hardware-level
disable than older ones.

---

## Please report your results

If you test `me_cleaner_experimental.py` on any of the experimental
platforms, please **open an issue** in this repo and include:

- Your machine model
- ME version (from MEAnalyzer on the stock firmware)
- Platform (TGL / ADL / RPL / MTL)
- Whether HAP was set correctly in MEAnalyzer after patching
- Whether ME was absent after flashing (`lspci`, BIOS ME field)

Enough successful reports will get a platform promoted from experimental
to the stable `me_cleaner.py`.

